# Humanize writing — remove AI tells

Write prose a human can deliver as their own, or rewrite existing prose so it stops reading as AI.
Humanizing is mostly subtraction: cut the framing, keep the specific fact. Don't invent "human
texture" — that's its own tell. Preserve meaning, facts, numbers, names, quotes, and citations exactly.
Apply to prose only — never to code, code comments, or technical config.

The root cause of every tell below: LLMs regress to the mean, swapping specific facts for generic,
positive-sounding phrasing. Push back toward the specific — name the date, number, person, or what
actually happened, and cut the framing around it.

## 1. Use the plain word

Replace inflated vocab with the ordinary one (or cut it). Swapping one banned word for another
("leverage" → "harness") doesn't help.

| Don't write | Write |
|---|---|
| delve into | look at, dig into |
| showcase / highlight (verb) / underscore | show, point to |
| foster | build, support |
| garner | get, earn |
| leverage | use |
| enhance | improve |
| align with / resonate with | match, fit — or cut |
| serves as / stands as / serves as a testament to | is, shows, proves |
| features / offers / boasts | has |
| pivotal / crucial / vital / key (adj.) | important — or cut |
| tapestry / rich tapestry | cut |
| landscape / evolving landscape | name the field ("the industry") |
| realm / journey | area, field |
| vibrant / intricate | describe what's specifically lively/complex |
| valuable insights | state the insight |
| Additionally / Moreover / Furthermore (openers) | start the sentence, or "also" |
| It is worth noting that | delete |

## 2. Direct, uneven sentences

- Use is/are/has — don't dress simple facts in elaborate verbs.
- No "not just X, but Y" / "not X, but Y" parallelism. Pick one, or use a plain "but".
- No rule-of-three padding ("keynotes, panels, and networking"). Be specific or say one thing well.
- Repeat the noun — don't cycle synonyms for the same thing.
- No false "from X to Y" ranges unless they're real endpoints on a real scale.
- End at the fact. Cut "-ing" tack-ons that add interpretation ("…creating a vibrant community").
- Vary sentence length. Metronomic pacing is the #1 detection signal; put a short sentence next to a long one.

## 3. Earn every claim

- State the fact, skip the significance ("stands as a testament", "marks a pivotal moment").
- Don't label your own point "interesting / contrarian / surprising" — let it carry itself.
- No name-dropping to prove importance; say what the source actually said.
- Name the source or cut it — no "experts argue", "industry reports", "observers note".
- No knowledge-cutoff disclaimers ("as of my last update"). Give the date a fact is from instead.
- Write the real thing — no placeholders, no hedged gap-filling ("is believed to have").
- Don't stack hedges or "Notably / Interestingly / Importantly" calibration cues.
- No "Despite its X, Y faces challenges… continues to thrive" formula or optimism kicker.

## 4. A person, not an assistant

- No "Let's explore", "Here is your X", "As we can see", "This allows us to".
- No sycophancy or prompt-restating ("Great question!", "To answer your question").
- No rhetorical-question openers as transitions ("But what does this mean for you?").

## 5. Structure and formatting

- Let the subject shape the structure — no fixed Intro → … → Future Outlook template.
- Keep one consistent voice; sudden style shifts read as stitched-together AI.
- Sentence case headings; bold only for genuine emphasis; no inline-header bullet lists for prose.
- No emoji in headings/bullets unless the user already uses them.
- One em dash per piece, max — prefer commas, parentheses, colons.
- Strip artifacts: chatbot citation tokens, AI-tool URL params, "Let me think step by step".

## Self-check

Banned word? Replace. More than one em dash? Cut. "-ing" interpretation clause? End at the fact.
Puffery or self-labeled significance? Cut. Cutoff disclaimer / placeholder / vague "experts say"?
Fix or leave an honest blank. Title-case headings? Sentence case. Do the sentences march or vary?
Break the rhythm. Could a reader spot this as AI in five seconds? Redraft.
